      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let me break it down for you in a more straightforward way.\n\nWhen you engage in high-intensity exercise, your muscles rely on anaerobic glycolysis to produce energy. This process involves the breakdown of glucose into pyruvate, which is then converted into lactic acid. The production of lactic acid is catalyzed by the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase.\n\nThe lactic acid builds up in your muscles, causing fatigue and soreness. However, the body has a way to neutralize it through the Cori cycle, which involves the conversion of lactic acid back into glucose. This process is facilitated by the enzyme pyruvate kinase.\n\nAs for getting rid of lactic acid after a set, your body uses a combination of mechanisms. During intense exercise, your muscles take up oxygen and use it to convert lactic acid back into glucose through aerobic respiration. This process is more efficient and helps to reduce lactic acid levels. Additionally, your body can also eliminate excess lactic acid through the kidneys and liver, which excrete it into the bloodstream and eventually into the urine.\n\nSo, to summarize, the production of lactic acid is a",
